# TypeScript Standards

## Strict Mode

- Enable `strict: true` in tsconfig — no exceptions
- No `any` types — use `unknown` and narrow with type guards
- Prefer `interface` for object shapes, `type` for unions/intersections

## Naming

- `camelCase` for variables and functions
- `PascalCase` for types, interfaces, and classes
- `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE` for constants
- Prefix boolean variables with `is`, `has`, `should`
- Suffix event handler functions with `Handler` or use `on` prefix

## Error Handling

- Always handle promise rejections — no fire-and-forget
- Use try/catch in async functions, log context with errors
- Chrome API callbacks: check `chrome.runtime.lastError`

## Exports

- Prefer named exports over default exports
- One module = one responsibility
- Re-export from barrel `index.ts` files only at feature boundaries

## Code Style

- No classes unless genuinely needed (prefer functions + closures)
- Prefer `const` assertions for literal objects used as config
- Use early returns to reduce nesting
- Destructure function parameters when there are 3+ properties
